{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17490889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17490889"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:20:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:20:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"771"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/771"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.33,0.12,0.49,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"771"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102061"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/771"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"771"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84515"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3461"},{"type":"tags","id":"4208"},{"type":"tags","id":"4493"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2344"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13879"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18386"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35551"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42145"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44478"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102061"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 65-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 24-hour history of increasing upper abdominal pain. The pain is constant in nature and she feels nauseated. On examination she looks unwell, with a blood pressure of 110/70 mmHg, pulse 108/min and temperature 38.5\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. There is tenderness in the right upper quadrant while the rest of the abdomen is soft to palpation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ultrasound examination is performed and reported as follows:\u00a0\u003Cem\u003ENumerous stones can be seen throughout the gallbladder, the largest being 2 cm diameter. The gallbladder wall measures 5 mm (\u0026lt;3) thickness. The common duct is dilated to 8 mm (\u0026lt;8). Fatty change can be seen throughout the liver.\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Biliary colic","Cholangitis","Mirizzi syndrome","Acute cholecystitis","Non-alcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH)"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture of rapid onset upper abdominal pain, fever and right upper quadrant tenderness is consistent with a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute cholecystitis\u003C/strong\u003E. This diagnosis is confirmed radiologically by the thickening of the gallbladder wall in the setting of gallstones with the increased wall thickness implying an inflammatory/infectious process. The reported mild \u0027dilatation of the common bile\u0027 (just over upper limit of normal) is unlikely to be of any clinical significance, with such findings being found in up to 30% of cases of acute cholecystitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiliary colic\u003C/strong\u003E is the pain caused by a gallstone which temporarily impacts in the neck of the gallbladder, causing transient biliary obstruction. This pain is usually short-lived (less than one hour) and ceases when the stone spontaneously falls back into the gallbladder. If ongoing obstruction occurs the gallbladder becomes inflamed (i.e. acute cholecystitis occurs).\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003EWhile clinically these two conditions may present similarly, the length of the history and the fever in this patient suggests an inflammatory or infective process is present. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAscending cholangitis \u003C/strong\u003Eis inflammation of the bile duct\u00a0caused by\u003Cem\u003E \u003C/em\u003Ebacterial infection. Cholangitis is classically characterised by Charcot\u0027s triad: fever, jaundice and right upper quadrant pain. However, only two-thirds of cases have all three features and jaundice may be absent in some 20% of cases. What makes cholangitis unlikely in the scenario described here in the thickening of the gallbladder wall seen on ultrasound - this is far more in keeping with a diagnosis of acute cholecystitis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMirizzi syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is rare complication of gallstones involving impaction of a stone in the cystic duct or neck of the gallbladder. This causes compression of the common hepatic duct, resulting in an obstructive jaundice. It can also usually be detected on ultrasound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFatty changes in the liver may suggest \u003Cstrong\u003Enon-alcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH),\u003C/strong\u003E however this should not cause pain and is therefore unlikely to be the primary aetiology of concern in this patient. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute cholecystitis is a common cause of right upper quadrant pain.","Acute cholecystitis can be confirmed via ultrasound where gallstones and thickening of the gall bladder wall may be identified."],"references":["M Crawford. Biliary pain. Australian Family Physician. 2013;42(6):458 - 461. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2013/july/biliary-pain","Becker BA, Chin E, Mervis E, Anderson CL, Oshita MH, Fox JC. Emergency biliary sonography: utility of common bile duct measurement in the diagnosis of cholecystitis and choledocholithiasis. J Emerg Med. 2014 Jan;46(1):54-60. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24126067/","Sutherland T. Demystifying abdominal ultrasound. Aust Fam Physician. 2009;38(10):798\u2013802. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/a551027c-ed92-49ca-964d-4e23b3705381/Demystifying-abdominal-ultrasound.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84515"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"771"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84515"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-07T14:16:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-07T14:21:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"771"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102061"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","syno